<div class="body-container">
  <h1> Understanding the Issue </h1>
  <h2> Symptoms </h2>
  <p> You may encounter situations where your printer is not turning on after the switch is flipped to ON. </p>
  
  <h2> Considerations </h2>
  <p> To apply the correct solution, you must first identify whether this is a power-related or a touch panel-related issue. </p>
  <p> Here are some scenarios that you should consider to analyze the situation better: </p>
    <ol> 
      <li> If the sensor light is glowing when the printer is turned on, it suggests that it is not a power issue but more than likely a touch panel issue. </li>
      <li>If the mainboard indicators light up when the printer is turned on after removing the front cover, it suggests that it is not a power issue but more than likely a touch panel issue. </li>
      <li> If none of those lights are visible when the printer is turned on, you should look into its power components and the mainboard using the suggestions below. </li>
  </ol>
</div>

     <blockquote class="is-info">
       <p> Watch the tutorial
         <a target="_blank" href="https://youtu.be/S5yqNxxRlCE?si=XdaXhZVfNQdTsjh-" class="is-external-link">

   <!-- insert image after uploading, paste the path to the middle quote after src -->
     <ol type=1> 
       <li> Prepare your multimeter for the AC range. </li>
       <li> Plug the cord into an electric outlet. </li>
       <li> Measure the output voltage of the cord. </li>
       <li> The correct output voltage should be 110~240 V AC depending on your country or region. </li>
     </ol>
   <!-- list instructions above -->
   <!-- set outcome assumptions below-->
   <h3> What to do next? </h3>
   <blockquote class="is-success">
     <ol>
       <li> The voltage is between 100 and 240 V AC → Move on checking the fuse </li>
       <li> The voltage is not between 100 and 240 V AC → The power cord is broken, and other components are unknown </li>
     </ol>
   </blockquote>
  </details>

 <details>
   <summary>
  	 <h2> Check the Fuse </h2>
   </summary>
   <!-- add description here -->
   <h3> How to do it? </h3>
     <blockquote class="is-info">
       <p> Watch the tutorial
         <a target="_blank" href="https://youtu.be/S5yqNxxRlCE?si=XdaXhZVfNQdTsjh-" class="is-external-link">
           here.
         </a>
       </p>
     </blockquote>
    <ol tpye=1>
      <li> Make sure the printer is turned off and the power source is disconnected. </li>
      <li> Use a slotted screwdriver or a hex key to pry and remove the fuse from the power switch. 
        <br> <img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/v2_fuse.jpg" alt="Remove Fuse"> </li>
      <li> Set your multimeter to test continuity or audible continuity.
      	<br> <img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/multimeter_continuity.jpg" alt="Set Multimeter to Test Continuity"> </li>
      <li> A functional fuse should have a reading close to 0 when performing a continuity test or create a loud beep noise when performing an audible continuity test. 
        <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/check_fuse.jpg" alt="Check Fuse"> </li>
    </ol>
   <!-- set outcome assumptions below-->
   <h3> What to do next? </h3>
   <blockquote class="is-success">
     <ol>
       <li> The voltage is between 100 and 240 V AC → Move on checking the fuse </li>
       <li> The voltage is not between 100 and 240 V AC → The power cord is broken, and other components are unknown </li>
     </ol>
   </blockquote>
  </details>

 <details>
   <summary>
	   <h2> Check the Power Switch Output Voltage </h2>
   </summary>
   <!-- add description here -->
   <h3> How to do it? </h3>
     <blockquote class="is-info">
       <p> Watch the tutorial
         <a target="_blank" href="https://youtu.be/Cqv8g9Mxh3c?si=SZOI6e1iiH2FfNZb" class="is-external-link">
           here.
         </a>
       </p>
     </blockquote>
    <ol tpye=1>
      <li> Make sure the printer is turned off and the power source is disconnected. </li>
      <li> Take out the power switch after removing the 2 flathead screws using an H2 hex key. 
        <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/power_switch_1.jpg" alt="Remove Power Switch"> </li>
      <li> Disconnect the two highlighted wires from the switcher.
        <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/ln_wire1.jpg" alt="Disconnect Wires"> </li>
      <li> Set your multimeter to measure the AC range. </li>
      <li> Plug the power cord into the switch socket and measure the two pins from the disconnected wires. 
        <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/ln_wire2.jpg" alt="Probes on Pins"> </li>
      <li> The correct output voltage should be 110~240 V AC depending on your country or region.
        <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/ac_test.jpg" alt="Power Switch Reading"> </li>
    </ol>
   <!-- set outcome assumptions below-->
   <h3> What to do next? </h3>
   <blockquote class="is-success">
     <ol>
       <li> The voltage is between 100 and 240 V AC → Move on checking the PSU </li>
       <li> The voltage is not between 100 and 240 V AC → The power switch is broken and other components are unknown </li>
     </ol>
   </blockquote>
  </details>  

 <details>
   <summary>
   	<h2> Check the Power Supply Unit (PSU) Output Voltage </h2>
   </summary>
   <!-- add description here -->
   <h3> How to do it? </h3>
     <blockquote class="is-info">
       <p> Watch the tutorial
         <a target="_blank" href="https://youtu.be/d2ubM8PMiXA?si=6AoNcTDtVe-NDyLH" class="is-external-link">
           <b> here. </b>
         </a>
       </p>
     </blockquote>
    <ol tpye=1>
      <li> Remove the front case of the printer.
          <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/remove_the_front_case.png" alt="Remove Front Case">
        <li> Plug in the power cord and turn on the printer. </li>
        <li> Set your multimeter to measure the DC range. </li>
        <li> Measure the input voltage of mainboard terminal 1.
          <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/mainboard_-_measure_power_voltage.jpg" alt="Measure Mainbaord Input Voltage"> </li>
        <li> The correct input voltage of the mainboard should be 24 V.
          <br><img width="400" src="/sonic-mega-v2/24v.jpg" alt="24 V"> </li>
    </ol>
   <!-- set outcome assumptions below-->
   <h3> What to do next? </h3>
   <blockquote class="is-success">
     <ol>
       <li> The voltage is 24 V DC → Check the mainboard input voltage </li>
       <li> The voltage is not 24 V DC → The PSU broke and the mainboard is unknown </li>
     </ol>
   </blockquote>
  </details>
